Purpose

This policy defines how to create a task (issue) that requires code changes.

Its goal is to ensure that coding issues are:
	‚Ä¢	Short but clear
	‚Ä¢	Understandable by humans and AI agents
	‚Ä¢	Safe to execute
	‚Ä¢	Properly scoped

‚∏ª

Scope

This policy applies to any issue that requires writing, modifying, or deleting code.

‚∏ª

Issue Text Requirements
	‚Ä¢	The issue description must be concise
	‚Ä¢	The intent and motivation must be explicit
	‚Ä¢	Avoid long narratives and implicit assumptions

‚∏ª

Required Section: Intent

Any issue that requires code changes must contain the following section.

## Intent

### What we are doing
(Describe the concrete changes to be made)

### Why we are doing this
(Explain the problem, value, or motivation)

Rules:
	‚Ä¢	Both subsections are required
	‚Ä¢	‚ÄúWhy‚Äù must not restate ‚ÄúWhat‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	The text must be understandable without external context

‚∏ª

Issue Scoping & Labeling

When creating a coding issue, think explicitly about scope.

Label Check
	‚Ä¢	Verify whether additional labels are required:
	‚Ä¢	bug
	‚Ä¢	refactor
	‚Ä¢	proposal
	‚Ä¢	epic
	‚Ä¢	autocode (human-applied only)
	‚Ä¢	Labels signal intent and permissions, not just categorization

Split vs Single Issue
	‚Ä¢	Do not split an issue into multiple ones if:
	‚Ä¢	The total expected code change is small or moderate
(‚âà < 600 lines of code)
	‚Ä¢	The work is logically cohesive
	‚Ä¢	In such cases, prefer:
	‚Ä¢	A single issue
	‚Ä¢	A TODO checklist inside the issue
	‚Ä¢	Incremental pushes
	‚Ä¢	Checking completed TODO items ‚úÖ

When to Split or Create an Epic

Consider splitting the work or creating an Epic if:
	‚Ä¢	The issue spans multiple independent concerns
	‚Ä¢	The work naturally forms stages or tiers
	‚Ä¢	The scope is unclear or exploratory
	‚Ä¢	The expected implementation is large or risky

